\i0 \
These benchmarks are provided to indicate how much music synthesis computation a DSP can do in real time, using the software provided by the Music Kit.   
\i These tests were done with a 25 MHz  DSP with 8K words of 0-wait state DSP SRAM.  
\i0 Note that Intel-based DSP cards have faster DSPs and more DSP SRAM, allowing for more voices.  However, some Intel-based DSP cards, such as the Turtle Beach Multisound, use slower DSP SRAM, which will negatively impact the number of possible voices.\
\
The benchmarks are in the following format:\
\

\b\i Name–
\b0 description: I1 / I2\

\i0 \

\b\i Name
\i0  
\b0 is the name of a synthesis instrument in the Music Kit SynthPatch Library.  
\i Description
\i0  describes the synthesis instrument briefly.  
\i I1 
\i0 is the number of instances of the instrument that can play in real time at a sound-out sampling rate of 22050 Hz.  
\i I2
\i0  is the number of instances that can play at a sampling rate of 44100 Hz.\
\
Note that the Music Kit SynthPatch Library supports a number of instruments that are not represented here.  It also supports polyphonic instruments, and the constitution of the orchestra can be changed between samples (via timed messages) during a performance.\

